/Users/zhanglongqin/audithoundv2/output/lambowin_src_no_interfaces_libraries_3r/rounds/round_7/merge_stderr.log:937:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"VirtualToken.cashIn mints by msg.value for ERC20 underlyings, enabling unbacked minting/mis-accounting","locations":["VirtualToken.sol:72","VirtualToken.sol:76","VirtualToken.sol:78","VirtualToken.sol:82","VirtualToken.sol:138"],"claim":"When underlyingToken != NATIVE_TOKEN, cashIn(amount) transfers amount underlying ERC20 but mints msg.value vTokens. This breaks 1:1 accounting: ERC20 deposits with msg.value=0 mint zero, while nonzero ETH can mint vTokens without matching ERC20 backing.","impact":"If any whitelisted address can invoke this path for an ERC20-backed VirtualToken, it can create unbacked redeemable supply and drain existing underlying liquidity, or cause insolvency/loss for honest depositors through under-minting.","paths":["Deploy/use VirtualToken with ERC20 underlying (underlyingToken != NATIVE_TOKEN).","Whitelisted caller invokes cashIn with mismatched amount vs msg.value (e.g., amount=0, nonzero msg.value, or nonzero amount, msg.value=0).","Contract mints by msg.value instead of deposited ERC20 amount.","Caller later redeems via cashOut against real ERC20 balance."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Permissionless createLaunchPad can consume per-block vETH loan quota and DoS other launches","locations":["LamboFactory.sol:65","LamboFactory.sol:70","LamboFactory.sol:74","VirtualToken.sol:93"],"claim":"createLaunchPad is callable by anyone (only token address is whitelist-gated), and each call draws from global MAX_LOAN_PER_BLOCK via takeLoan. An attacker can consume the full quota first each block.","impact":"Legitimate launch attempts in the same block can be forced to revert with Loan limit per block exceeded, enabling repeatable permissionless griefing/MEV denial of service.","paths":["Attacker calls createLaunchPad(..., virtualLiquidityAmount = MAX_LOAN_PER_BLOCK, virtualLiquidityToken = whitelisted vToken) early in block.","VirtualToken records the full per-block loan allowance as used.","Subsequent legitimate createLaunchPad calls in that block revert on the cap check.","Attack repeats block-by-block with priority gas."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Router sell pricing uses full vETH reserves including debt-locked liquidity, causing sell reverts and exit lockups","locations":["LamboFactory.sol:74","VirtualToken.sol:97","VirtualToken.sol:145","LamboVEthRouter.sol:110","LamboVEthRouter.sol:117","LamboVEthRouter.sol:126"],"claim":"Factory seeds pairs with debt-minted vETH (takeLoan(pool, amount)), and VirtualToken forbids transfers that move a debt address below its debt floor. Router sell quotes/swaps use raw pair reserves, which include debt-locked vETH that is not actually transferable out of the pair.","impact":"Users can receive quotes based on unavailable reserveOut and hit reverts during swap transfer (DebtOverflow), creating practical sell failures and potential lockup of exit liquidity once non-debt vETH is depleted.","paths":["Pool receives vETH via takeLoan(pool, virtualLiquidityAmount) and _debt[pool] is increased.","On sells, router computes amountXOut from full reserves (getReserves + getAmountOut).","Pair attempts to transfer vETH output, but VirtualToken _update enforces balance >= value + debt for from=pair.","If computed output exceeds transferable non-debt balance, transfer reverts and user sell fails."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"buyQuote refund logic withholds 1 wei from overpayments","locations":["LamboVEthRouter.sol:180","LamboVEthRouter.sol:181"],"claim":"Overpayment refunds are computed with an extra -1 wei (msg.value - amountXIn - fee - 1) and only triggered when excess is greater than 1 wei.","impact":"Users are systematically under-refunded by 1 wei when overpaying; residual ETH accumulates in the router as trapped dust.","paths":["User calls buyQuote with msg.value above required input+fee.","Refund branch returns excess - 1 wei instead of full excess.","1 wei remains in the contract per affected transaction."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Rebalance initialization can be seized if deployment is non-atomic or proxy is left uninitialized","locations":["rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:40","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:53","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:55"],"claim":"initialize is public and sets owner from a caller-supplied address. If deployment/upgrade flow ever leaves an instance (especially proxy) uninitialized, any external caller can initialize first and take ownership.","impact":"Attacker ownership enables privileged control (upgrade authorization and extractProfit), allowing asset extraction or malicious upgrades.","paths":["Instance/proxy is deployed without immediate initializer execution.","Attacker calls initialize(attacker, vETH, pool, fee) first.","Attacker becomes owner and can authorize upgrades/extract managed tokens."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Launchpad creation reverts because factory transfers LP tokens to the zero address","locations":["LamboFactory.sol:79","LamboFactory.sol:80"],"claim":"createLaunchPad mints LP to the factory and then calls IERC20(pool).safeTransfer(address(0), ...). For Uniswap V2-style LP ERC20 tokens (used by this code path via mainnet Uniswap V2 factory constants), transfers to address(0) revert, so launch creation cannot complete.","impact":"Core launch flow is bricked: pool setup reverts and downstream flows that depend on successful launchpad creation (including router-assisted initial buy) fail.","paths":["Call LamboFactory.createLaunchPad(...) with a whitelisted virtual token.","Function executes IPool(pool).mint(address(this)) then attempts IERC20(pool).safeTransfer(address(0), IERC20(pool).balanceOf(address(this))).","LP token transfer to zero address reverts, reverting the full launch transaction."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Predictable clone address enables pair pre-creation that can indefinitely brick targeted launch attempts","locations":["LamboFactory.sol:57","LamboFactory.sol:71","LamboFactory.sol:72"],"claim":"createLaunchPad deploys a non-deterministic clone (Clones.clone) and then calls createPair. The next clone address is predictable from the factory contract nonce, and Uniswap V2 createPair can be called permissionlessly for undeployed token addresses. An attacker can pre-create the pair for the next predicted clone address so createPair reverts.","impact":"Launch creation for the targeted virtual liquidity token can be persistently DoS'd. Because the victim transaction reverts, the factory nonce rolls back, so retries keep targeting the same blocked clone address until some other successful create changes nonce.","paths":["Attacker predicts the next clone address for LamboFactory.","Attacker calls Uniswap V2 factory createPair(virtualLiquidityToken, predictedClone) first.","Victim calls createLaunchPad; clone deployment succeeds but createPair reverts due existing pair.","Transaction reverts and factory nonce is unchanged, letting the attacker repeat the same block condition on retries."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-008","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Rebalance ignores caller-provided output target and executes swaps with zero minimum return","locations":["rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:62","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:73","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:94","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:97","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:113"],"claim":"rebalance(directionMask, amountIn, amountOut) accepts amountOut but never enforces it, and both buy/sell paths call uniswapV3SwapTo(..., minReturn=0, ...).","impact":"The strategy has no explicit slippage floor per execution, so adversarial order flow can capture most of the expected rebalance edge and leave only marginal profit to the protocol, degrading economic performance.","paths":["Operator/bot submits rebalance based on expected quote.","MEV actors move price around the rebalance transaction.","Swap still executes because minReturn=0 and amountOut is unused.","Transaction can settle at materially worse terms as long as final WETH delta stays positive."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-009","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Router and rebalance flows never enforce that configured vETH is native-backed, enabling full functional DoS via misconfiguration","locations":["LamboVEthRouter.sol:28","LamboVEthRouter.sol:129","LamboVEthRouter.sol:171","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:40","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:100","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:111"],"claim":"Both router and rebalance hard-code ETH cashIn/cashOut assumptions against vETH but never validate VirtualToken(vETH).underlyingToken() is the native-token sentinel.","impact":"If an ERC20-backed VirtualToken is configured as vETH, buy/sell/rebalance paths can revert or become incompatible, effectively bricking core trading/rebalance functionality.","paths":["Deploy/configure router or rebalance with a VirtualToken whose underlying is ERC20 instead of native ETH.","Execution reaches cashIn{value:...} and/or ETH-dependent cashOut handling paths.","Calls fail or downstream ETH transfer/wrapping logic breaks, reverting user operations."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-010","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"previewRebalance uses raw pool token balances, allowing donation-based signal manipulation","locations":["rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:128","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:129","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:130","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:135"],"claim":"previewRebalance derives direction and size from IERC20.balanceOf(uniswapPool) values rather than robust pool-state pricing primitives, so direct token transfers to the pool can skew the preview signal.","impact":"Automation that relies on previewRebalance can be induced into poor or reverting rebalance attempts, creating gas grief and degraded strategy execution quality.","paths":["Attacker transfers WETH or vETH directly to uniswapPool.","previewRebalance computes manipulated amountIn and direction from distorted balances.","Keeper/bot consuming preview output submits suboptimal rebalance parameters and loses execution quality (or reverts)."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-011","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Router fees are bypassable through direct trading against the public launch pair","locations":["LamboFactory.sol:72","LamboFactory.sol:79","LamboVEthRouter.sol:132","LamboVEthRouter.sol:151","LamboVEthRouter.sol:171","VirtualToken.sol:143"],"claim":"The buy/sell fee is charged only in LamboVEthRouter, while launch liquidity is placed in a normal public Uniswap V2 pair and vETH transfers are not restricted to the router except for per-address debt floors. Traders that can source or dispose of vETH externally can interact with the pair directly and avoid feeRate.","impact":"Protocol fee revenue is not enforceable at the contract layer. Once vETH is available through a vETH/WETH market, holders, or prior non-debt deposits into the pair, direct pair swaps can systematically bypass buy and sell fees.","paths":["Acquire vETH through the vETH/WETH market, another holder, or previous non-debt vETH liquidity.","For a buy, transfer vETH directly to the launch Uniswap V2 pair and call swap for the quote token instead of LamboVEthRouter.buyQuote.","For a sell, transfer quote tokens directly to the pair and call swap for vETH up to the pair's non-debt vETH balance, then route that vETH externally instead of using LamboVEthRouter.sellQuote.","No router fee code executes on the direct pair path."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-012","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Rebalance swap direction and caller-supplied pool mask are not validated against pool token order","locations":["rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:27","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:62","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:73","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:76","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:80","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:83","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:165"],"claim":"The packed OKX/Uniswap V3 pool word is built by ORing a public caller-supplied directionMask into uniswapPool, and previewRebalance derives that mask from tokenIn == weth rather than checking whether tokenIn is the configured pool's token0. The contract only treats the exact _BUY_MASK value as a buy; every other bit pattern executes the sell branch while still being forwarded as descriptor bits.","impact":"For deployments where vETH sorts on the unexpected side of WETH, rebalance calls can request the wrong input token in the swap callback or produce output that the follow-up cashIn/cashOut logic does not handle, causing persistent rebalance failure. Arbitrary public masks can also trigger malformed or unintended swap descriptors, although concrete fund loss beyond failed execution depends on the external router's descriptor semantics.","paths":["Deploy/configure a vETH/WETH Uniswap V3 pool where token ordering does not match the contract's implicit WETH-side assumption.","previewRebalance selects _BUY_MASK solely when tokenIn == weth and _SELL_MASK otherwise.","rebalance passes that mask, or any caller-supplied mask, through to onMorphoFlashLoan, which ORs it into the pool word and chooses _executeBuy only for the exact _BUY_MASK value.","The OKX/Uniswap V3 swap executes with the opposite direction or a malformed pool word, causing callback payment failure, wrong output handling, or full rebalance reverts."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-013","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Uniswap V2 fee switch can mint LP shares despite the intended burned-liquidity model","locations":["LamboFactory.sol:72","LamboFactory.sol:79","LamboFactory.sol:80","Utils/LaunchPadUtils.sol:21"],"claim":"Launch pools are created on the canonical Uniswap V2 factory, and the factory assumes moving the initially minted LP tokens away permanently removes all claims on reserves. If the Uniswap V2 feeTo switch is enabled, later mint/burn activity can mint protocol-fee LP tokens to feeTo even though the original LP was intended to be burned.","impact":"The external Uniswap feeTo address can receive a claim on launch-pool reserves and burn those LP shares to withdraw a portion of quote tokens and transferable vETH, violating the protocol's locked-liquidity assumption.","paths":["The canonical Uniswap V2 factory configured in LaunchPadUtils.UNISWAP_POOL_FACTORY_ has feeTo enabled.","A launch pool accumulates swap-fee growth after initial liquidity is minted and moved away.","A later liquidity mint or burn triggers Uniswap V2 protocol-fee minting to feeTo.","feeTo burns the minted LP shares and withdraws its proportional share of pool reserves."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-014","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Whitelisted router can be used as a generic arbitrary-pair vETH redemption adapter","locations":["LamboVEthRouter.sol:93","LamboVEthRouter.sol:107","LamboVEthRouter.sol:109","LamboVEthRouter.sol:126","LamboVEthRouter.sol:129","VirtualToken.sol:82"],"claim":"VirtualToken.cashOut is whitelist-gated, but the whitelisted router's sellQuote accepts any quoteToken, derives the canonical Uniswap V2 pair only from quoteToken/vETH, and never checks that the quote token or pair came from LamboFactory. A caller can therefore make the router receive vETH from an arbitrary pair and have the router redeem it.","impact":"The cashOut whitelist is not an effective boundary for vETH redemption. Any non-whitelisted account that can source transferable vETH can redeem it through an attacker-created pair; if transferable unbacked or mis-accounted vETH reaches users through another integration or bug, the router path can convert it into underlying ETH.","paths":["Attacker obtains transferable vETH.","Attacker creates and seeds a Uniswap V2 pair between vETH and an attacker-controlled quote token.","Attacker calls sellQuote(attackerToken, amountYIn, minReturn).","The router swaps the attacker token for vETH from the arbitrary pair, calls VirtualToken(vETH).cashOut(amountXOut), and forwards ETH to the caller minus the router fee."],"round":6,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-015","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Native ETH accepted by router and rebalancer has no recovery path","locations":["LamboVEthRouter.sol:188","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:55","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:168"],"claim":"Both LamboVEthRouter and LamboRebalanceOnUniwap accept native ETH through receive() functions, but neither exposes a native-ETH withdrawal or rescue function. The rebalancer's extractProfit only transfers ERC20 balances via IERC20(token).balanceOf and safeTransfer.","impact":"Accidental direct ETH transfers, forced ETH, and unexpected native ETH residuals can become permanently stuck. In the router this also compounds the trapped-dust behavior from refund underpayment, and in the rebalancer pre-existing native ETH is excluded from the _executeBuy wrapping delta.","paths":["Send ETH directly to LamboVEthRouter.receive() or leave refund dust in the router.","Send or force ETH to LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.receive().","Attempt recovery through available functions; the router has no withdrawal method and the rebalancer can only sweep ERC20 balances through extractProfit."],"round":6,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-016","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Rebalance preview can be unusable against non-view V3 quoters","locations":["rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:116","rebalance/LamboRebalanceOnUniwap.sol:155"],"claim":"previewRebalance is declared view and calls the hard-coded quoter through a view-typed call path, causing Solidity to issue STATICCALL for the quote. QuoterV2-style contracts compute quotes by invoking pool swap logic and reverting with quote data, which is incompatible with static execution once pool state-write logic is reached.","impact":"The intended preview path can revert instead of returning amountIn, amountOut, and directionMask, disabling simple keeper discovery and allowing vETH/WETH imbalance to persist unless callers implement their own off-chain quoting.","paths":["A keeper calls previewRebalance().","The function reaches quoteExactInputSingleWithPool through a static call because previewRebalance and the called interface are view.","A QuoterV2-style implementation attempts non-view pool swap simulation and reverts under STATICCALL.","No rebalance parameters are returned for automation."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-017","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Valid factories can repay and burn debt for arbitrary borrowers, allowing cross-factory launch-pair reserve corruption","locations":["VirtualToken.sol:39","VirtualToken.sol:57","VirtualToken.sol:105","VirtualToken.sol:106","VirtualToken.sol:107"],"claim":"repayLoan lets any address marked in validFactories decrease _debt[to] and burn amount of vTokens from arbitrary to without tracking which factory originated the debt, requiring borrower consent, or verifying an associated repayment flow.","impact":"A compromised, buggy, or overly broad valid factory can burn vETH directly out of existing launch pairs, leaving AMM reserves stale versus token balances. Subsequent swaps can revert until the deficit is refilled, or a sync can permanently crystallize the reserve loss and impair exit liquidity.","paths":["A VirtualToken owner has authorized more than one factory, or an authorized factory becomes buggy/compromised.","That valid factory calls repayLoan(launchPair, debtAmount) for a pair whose debt was created by another factory or launch flow.","VirtualToken decreases the pair's debt and burns the pair's vETH balance without any AMM reserve update or borrower approval.","The pair's recorded reserves exceed its actual vETH balance, causing later swaps to revert or forcing a sync that realizes the missing reserve."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Router fee can be raised to 100% and confiscate zero-minimum sells","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"Not kept as a reportable vulnerability because the fee change is an explicit onlyOwner parameter, the confiscation scenario requires a trusted owner or compromised owner plus user/integration minReturn=0, and nonzero minReturn sells revert rather than settle at zero."},{"title":"Caller-controlled rebalance mask is passed into the external swap descriptor unsanitized","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"Not kept as a separate finding. The supported part overlaps with F-012's mask/order validation issue and was folded there; the standalone claim about extra OKX descriptor bits causing loss remains speculative without a concrete router-semantics or fund-loss path, and failed rebalances revert."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/audithoundv2/output/resupply_fi_1777184922/rounds/round_5/merge_stderr.log:618:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Oracle decimal scaling is ignored, so non-18-decimal feeds misprice collateral by orders of magnitude","locations":["src/interfaces/IOracle.sol:5","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:573","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:176"],"claim":"The pair hardcodes exchange-rate inversion as `1e36 / oraclePrice` and never normalizes by `IOracle.decimals()`, even though the oracle interface exposes a decimals field and `setOracle()` accepts arbitrary replacement feeds. Any oracle returning prices in a scale other than 18 decimals will distort the collateral/debt conversion by a power-of-ten factor.","impact":"Borrow, solvency, redemption, and liquidation math can all be wrong by orders of magnitude. Depending on the oracle scale, healthy positions can be liquidated or blocked from withdrawing, or collateral can be overvalued enough for borrowers to mint far more debt than intended, leaving the pair insolvent.","paths":["A pair is deployed with, or later updated to, an oracle whose `getPrices()` output is not 18-decimal scaled.","`_updateExchangeRate()` computes `exchangeRate = 1e36 / price` without using `IOracle.decimals()`.","The distorted exchange rate propagates into `_isSolvent()`, borrow limits, redemptions, and liquidations."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Rewards claimed while no borrow shares exist become permanently stranded in the pair","locations":["src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:162","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:200","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:302","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:321","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:325"],"claim":"Reward accrual is only added to `global_reward_integral` when `_totalRewardShares() > 0`, but `_checkpoint()` still calls `_fetchIncentives()` and `_calcRewardIntegral()` still updates `reward_remaining = bal` even when reward shares are zero. Because `getReward` is publicly callable and `totalRewardShares` is just `totalBorrow.shares`, any rewards fetched during a zero-debt period are marked as already-accounted without increasing any user/global integral, so the backlog can never be distributed later.","impact":"CRV/CVX/governance rewards accrued while collateral remains staked but no borrows exist can be permanently trapped in the pair. This causes real value loss to the reward program/borrower set, and it is permissionless because any caller can trigger a checkpoint or `getReward` during the zero-share window.","paths":["Collateral remains staked in Convex while `totalBorrow.shares == 0`.","External rewards accrue and any caller triggers `getReward`, `earned`, or another checkpoint path, which calls `claimRewards(address(this))`.","`_calcRewardIntegral` skips integral growth because `_totalRewardShares() == 0` but still stores the fetched balance in `reward_remaining`.","When borrowing later resumes, only rewards above that stored balance are distributable; the earlier fetched balance remains stuck in the pair with no recovery path."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Unchecked Convex staking results can leave credited collateral unstaked and later lock withdrawals/liquidations","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:399","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:409","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:421","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:713","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:769"],"claim":"When Convex mode is enabled, the pair credits user collateral first and then calls `IConvexStaking.deposit(...)` without checking its boolean return value. `totalCollateral()` only counts the reward-contract stake balance, so if a Convex deposit returns `false` or stakes less than expected, the pair's accounting assumes collateral was staked while later exits try to withdraw shares that never reached Convex.","impact":"User collateral can become effectively stuck: withdrawals, liquidations, or pool migrations can revert because `_unstakeUnderlying()` pulls from the reward contract while the missing collateral remains idle in the pair. This creates accounting divergence and can permissionlessly DoS collateral exits for affected positions.","paths":["A borrower adds collateral while `convexPid != 0`, or the owner migrates pools with `_updateConvexPool()`.","The Convex `deposit(..., true)` call returns `false` or under-stakes, but the pair ignores the result and still keeps the higher `_userCollateralBalance`.","Later `_removeCollateral()` or pool migration calls `_unstakeUnderlying()` for the credited amount, but the reward contract balance is lower than expected, causing the operation to fail."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Convex pool migration mishandles the sentinel `pid == 0` and can orphan all collateral","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:382","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:386","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:399","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:402","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:421"],"claim":"`convexPid == 0` is treated elsewhere as 'do not stake', but `_updateConvexPool()` always reads `poolInfo(currentPid)`, withdraws only the old reward-contract balance, and then blindly deposits `stakedBalance` into `_pid`, including when `_pid == 0`. It also ignores any collateral already sitting locally when migrating from `0` to a live pool. Since `totalCollateral()` switches between local-balance and reward-contract accounting based only on `convexPid`, changing pools across the sentinel can make the contract look in the wrong place for essentially all collateral.","impact":"An owner pool update can make the pair believe collateral vanished, causing withdrawals and liquidations to revert or positions to appear insolvent even though the tokens still exist somewhere else. This is a protocol-level lockup/orphaning risk for all live collateral in the pair.","paths":["If the owner calls `setConvexPool(0)` to disable staking, `_updateConvexPool()` withdraws from the old rewards contract and then deposits the same amount into Convex pool `0`, but sets `convexPid = 0`; afterwards `totalCollateral()` reads only the pair's local collateral balance and ignores the still-staked funds.","If the pair currently has `convexPid == 0` and already holds local collateral, calling `setConvexPool(nonZeroPid)` migrates only `stakedBalance` read from `poolInfo(0)` and never stakes the pair's local holdings; afterwards `totalCollateral()` reads only the Convex reward balance and ignores the locally held collateral.","Any subsequent withdrawal, liquidation, or solvency path that relies on `totalCollateral()` / `_unstakeUnderlying()` can then fail against the mismatched accounting location."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Unconditional reward claiming can globally freeze borrowing, repayments, withdrawals, and liquidations","locations":["src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:224","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:226","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:321","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:599","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:833"],"claim":"Every borrower checkpoint unconditionally calls `IResupplyRegistry(registry).claimRewards(address(this))`. Checkpoints sit inside `_syncUserRedemptions()` and `_repay()`, which are reached by `isSolvent`-gated borrow/collateral flows, normal repayments, and liquidations. As a result, any revert in the registry reward-claim path bricks core pair operations even though reward collection is ancillary bookkeeping.","impact":"If the reward claimer, registry hook, or downstream reward source starts reverting, active borrowers can be unable to borrow, remove collateral, repay, repay with collateral, or be liquidated. That can trap user positions and let insolvencies persist because liquidation is blocked by an unrelated reward failure.","paths":["`borrow`, `removeCollateral*`, `leveragedPosition`, and `repayWithCollateral` all execute the `isSolvent` modifier, which calls `_syncUserRedemptions()` -> `_checkpoint()` -> `_fetchIncentives()` -> external `claimRewards` before the main action completes.","`repay` and the liquidation path both call `_repay()`, which also checkpoints the borrower before updating debt and therefore hits the same external reward-claim dependency.","If `claimRewards(address(this))` reverts for any reason, those state-changing entrypoints revert as well, causing a pair-wide DoS for debt management and liquidations."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Zero oracle prices cause division-by-zero reverts across critical pair flows","locations":["src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:573","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:688","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:955","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:1001"],"claim":"`_updateExchangeRate()` computes `1e36 / IOracle(...).getPrices(...)` without checking that the oracle returned a non-zero price. If the configured oracle ever returns `0` instead of reverting, the division hard-reverts every caller that refreshes the exchange rate.","impact":"A zero oracle answer can halt borrowing, leveraged positions, redemptions, liquidations, and collateral withdrawals for borrowers that still have debt. This can trap positions and block liquidations during exactly the period when the price feed is unhealthy.","paths":["The configured oracle or one of its downstream feeds returns `0` for `getPrices(address(collateral))`.","Any call path that executes `_updateExchangeRate()`—including `borrow`, `leveragedPosition`, `repayWithCollateral`, `redeemCollateral`, `liquidate`, and collateral removal for users with outstanding debt—reverts on division by zero.","Because solvency updates and liquidation both depend on a fresh exchange rate, active positions can become unmanageable until the oracle stops returning zero."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-009","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Share-refactor floor rounding can leak small amounts of debt and leave unowned borrow shares","locations":["src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:336","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:944","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:946"],"claim":"When a redemption triggers share refactoring, the pair divides `totalBorrow.shares` by `SHARE_REFACTOR_PRECISION` once, but each borrower's `_userBorrowShares` is only divided later during `_increaseUserRewardEpoch()` using floor rounding. There is no remainder accounting, so the sum of lazily-updated user shares can fall below the already-refactored global share total, and borrowers with fewer than `SHARE_REFACTOR_PRECISION` pre-refactor shares round all the way to zero.","impact":"The loss per account is bounded and typically small, but it can permanently leak some debt out of user ownership. In edge cases, a dust borrower can become debt-free after a refactor while the corresponding amount remains embedded in global debt accounting, creating small accounting drift and redistributing residual debt away from rounded-down users.","paths":["Repeated redemptions reduce `totalBorrow.amount` until `totalBorrow.amount * SHARE_REFACTOR_PRECISION < totalBorrow.shares`, triggering `_increaseRewardEpoch()` and a one-time division of global borrow shares.","Borrowers are migrated to the new epoch lazily, and each `_userBorrowShares` value is independently divided by `SHARE_REFACTOR_PRECISION` with floor rounding.","After enough borrowers sync, the sum of user-owned shares can be smaller than `totalBorrow.shares`; very small positions can round to zero shares entirely and stop owing their residual debt."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-010","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Excess redemption write-offs are silently discarded, leaving phantom collateral in borrower accounting","locations":["src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:279","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:604","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:610","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:965"],"claim":"Redemptions socialize collateral losses by minting `redemptionWriteOff` rewards pro rata to borrow shares, but `_syncUserRedemptions()` caps each borrower's loss at zero collateral and then erases the full claimable write-off balance. If an account's assigned write-off exceeds its current `_userCollateralBalance`, the excess loss is dropped instead of being redistributed or booked as bad debt. `_isSolvent()` later trusts the raw `_userCollateralBalance` value, so the remaining borrowers can still appear better collateralized than the pair's actual post-redemption collateral supports.","impact":"After a large redemption, the system can become materially undercollateralized while some borrowers still look solvent on paper. Those borrowers can then withdraw real collateral or take on more debt against collateral that has already been redeemed away, draining the remaining pool and worsening insolvency for everyone left.","paths":["A redemption removes collateral from the pair and mints `redemptionWriteOff` in proportion to current borrow shares.","A highly leveraged borrower's pending write-off exceeds its `_userCollateralBalance`, so `_syncUserRedemptions()` floors that account to zero at `currentUserBalance >= rTokens ? currentUserBalance - rTokens : 0` and discards the excess by zeroing `claimable_reward[address(redemptionWriteOff)][account]`.","The pair's actual collateral fell by the full redeemed amount, but aggregate borrower collateral is reduced by less than that full amount.","Later solvency checks and collateral actions use the overstated `_userCollateralBalance`, allowing other borrowers to borrow more or withdraw against phantom backing until real collateral runs out."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-012","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Allowing `minimumLeftoverDebt = 0` can preserve stale global borrow shares after full redemption","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:289","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:936","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:944","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:946","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:649","src/libraries/VaultAccount.sol:16"],"claim":"The owner can set `minimumLeftoverDebt` to zero, which allows `redeemCollateral()` to drive `totalBorrow.amount` fully to zero. The subsequent share refactor only divides `totalBorrow.shares` by `SHARE_REFACTOR_PRECISION` once, so nonzero global borrow shares can remain even though total debt is zero. Later borrows call `toShares()` with `total.amount == 0`, which mints new shares without clearing those leftovers, carrying stale share supply into the next debt cycle.","impact":"Post-redemption debt accounting can start from a corrupted share base instead of a clean reset. Newly opened borrows can be diluted by unowned stale shares, leaving part of the new global debt effectively unattached to any borrower and causing misallocation in later repayment and solvency math.","paths":["Governance sets `minimumLeftoverDebt` to `0` through `setMinimumLeftoverDebt()`.","A redemption reduces `totalBorrow.amount` to zero, but the one-shot refactor in `redeemCollateral()` leaves `totalBorrow.shares > 0`.","A later borrower opens a new position; `_totalBorrow.toShares(debtForMint, true)` follows the `total.amount == 0` branch and mints fresh shares on top of the stale share supply instead of resetting it.","The resulting `totalBorrow.amount` / `totalBorrow.shares` state includes leftover unowned shares, skewing future debt ownership and accounting."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-013","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Reward-manager invalidation can disable the internal write-off token and break redemption accounting","locations":["src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:125","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:129","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:150","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:177","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:604","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:965"],"claim":"`invalidateReward()` can be called on any tracked reward token, including the internally-created `redemptionWriteOff` token registered in the pair constructor. Once that slot is invalidated, `_calcRewardIntegral()` returns early for it, so new write-off supply minted by `redeemCollateral()` never reaches `claimable_reward[address(redemptionWriteOff)]` and `_syncUserRedemptions()` stops reducing borrower collateral for subsequent redemptions. If the token is revived later, the skipped backlog is then distributed using the borrow-share distribution at revival time rather than the historical distribution when the redemptions occurred.","impact":"A mistaken or unsafe reward-manager action can temporarily disable the pair's redemption-loss accounting, leaving borrower collateral overstated after redemptions. During that window borrowers can avoid liquidations, borrow against collateral that has already been redeemed away, or withdraw more collateral than the pair still owns; reviving the token later can then socialize the missed losses onto the wrong borrowers.","paths":["The reward manager calls `invalidateReward(address(redemptionWriteOff))`.","One or more redemptions occur, and `redeemCollateral()` keeps minting additional write-off supply.","Borrowers are checkpointed through normal actions, but `_syncUserRedemptions()` sees no new `claimable_reward[address(redemptionWriteOff)]`, so their collateral balances are not reduced for those redemptions.","If the reward token is later revived, the entire skipped write-off backlog is assigned across the then-current borrow-share distribution instead of the historical one."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-016","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Constructor bypasses the max-LTV safety cap enforced by the runtime setter","locations":["src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:141","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:173","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:193"],"claim":"The constructor decodes `_maxLTV` from deployment config and writes it directly into storage without checking that it is at most `LTV_PRECISION`, while `setMaxLTV()` later rejects values above that cap. A pair can therefore be deployed with a max LTV above 100% even though the live setter forbids that state.","impact":"A misconfigured deployment can launch an already unsafe market where users permissionlessly open undercollateralized positions and extract bad debt up to the configured borrow limit. Because the protocol explicitly enforces the bound in the runtime setter, the missing constructor check is a real initialization gap rather than an intended operating mode.","paths":["A pair is deployed with constructor config `_maxLTV > 1e5`.","Users add a small amount of collateral and borrow more value than the collateral can support while still passing `_isSolvent()` against the inflated limit.","The pair accumulates immediate bad debt even though the same max-LTV value could never be set after deployment via `setMaxLTV()`."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Redemptions release collateral without proving the stablecoins were actually burned","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`redeemCollateral()` is intentionally restricted to the registry's trusted `redemptionHandler`, and the burn/settlement step is delegated to that privileged protocol component. A buggy or malicious handler is a trusted-component failure, not a pair-level vulnerability."},{"title":"Liquidations erase borrower debt before confirming the handler paid or burned it","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`liquidate()` is callable only by the registry's trusted `liquidationHandler`, and the design explicitly delegates debt settlement to `processLiquidationDebt()`. Underpayment by that privileged handler is a trust-boundary failure rather than a missing permissionless invariant in the pair itself."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/audithoundv2/output/resupply_fi_1777184922/rounds/round_9/merge_stdout.log:1:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Oracle decimal scaling is ignored, so non-18-decimal feeds misprice collateral by orders of magnitude","locations":["src/interfaces/IOracle.sol:5","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:573","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:176"],"claim":"The pair hardcodes exchange-rate inversion as `1e36 / oraclePrice` and never normalizes by `IOracle.decimals()`, even though the oracle interface exposes a decimals field and `setOracle()` accepts arbitrary replacement feeds. Any oracle returning prices in a scale other than 18 decimals will distort the collateral/debt conversion by a power-of-ten factor.","impact":"Borrow, solvency, redemption, and liquidation math can all be wrong by orders of magnitude. Depending on the oracle scale, healthy positions can be liquidated or blocked from withdrawing, or collateral can be overvalued enough for borrowers to mint far more debt than intended, leaving the pair insolvent.","paths":["A pair is deployed with, or later updated to, an oracle whose `getPrices()` output is not 18-decimal scaled.","`_updateExchangeRate()` computes `exchangeRate = 1e36 / price` without using `IOracle.decimals()`.","The distorted exchange rate propagates into `_isSolvent()`, borrow limits, redemptions, and liquidations."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Rewards claimed while no borrow shares exist become permanently stranded in the pair","locations":["src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:162","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:200","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:302","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:321","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:325"],"claim":"Reward accrual is only added to `global_reward_integral` when `_totalRewardShares() > 0`, but `_checkpoint()` still calls `_fetchIncentives()` and `_calcRewardIntegral()` still updates `reward_remaining = bal` even when reward shares are zero. Because `getReward` is publicly callable and `totalRewardShares` is just `totalBorrow.shares`, any rewards fetched during a zero-debt period are marked as already-accounted without increasing any user/global integral, so the backlog can never be distributed later.","impact":"CRV/CVX/governance rewards accrued while collateral remains staked but no borrows exist can be permanently trapped in the pair. This causes real value loss to the reward program/borrower set, and it is permissionless because any caller can trigger a checkpoint or `getReward` during the zero-share window.","paths":["Collateral remains staked in Convex while `totalBorrow.shares == 0`.","External rewards accrue and any caller triggers `getReward`, `earned`, or another checkpoint path, which calls `claimRewards(address(this))`.","`_calcRewardIntegral` skips integral growth because `_totalRewardShares() == 0` but still stores the fetched balance in `reward_remaining`.","When borrowing later resumes, only rewards above that stored balance are distributable; the earlier fetched balance remains stuck in the pair with no recovery path."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Unchecked Convex staking results can leave credited collateral unstaked and later lock withdrawals/liquidations","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:399","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:409","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:421","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:713","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:769"],"claim":"When Convex mode is enabled, the pair credits user collateral first and then calls `IConvexStaking.deposit(...)` without checking its boolean return value. `totalCollateral()` only counts the reward-contract stake balance, so if a Convex deposit returns `false` or stakes less than expected, the pair's accounting assumes collateral was staked while later exits try to withdraw shares that never reached Convex.","impact":"User collateral can become effectively stuck: withdrawals, liquidations, or pool migrations can revert because `_unstakeUnderlying()` pulls from the reward contract while the missing collateral remains idle in the pair. This creates accounting divergence and can permissionlessly DoS collateral exits for affected positions.","paths":["A borrower adds collateral while `convexPid != 0`, or the owner migrates pools with `_updateConvexPool()`.","The Convex `deposit(..., true)` call returns `false` or under-stakes, but the pair ignores the result and still keeps the higher `_userCollateralBalance`.","Later `_removeCollateral()` or pool migration calls `_unstakeUnderlying()` for the credited amount, but the reward contract balance is lower than expected, causing the operation to fail."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Convex pool migration mishandles the sentinel `pid == 0` and can orphan all collateral","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:382","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:386","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:399","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:402","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:421"],"claim":"`convexPid == 0` is treated elsewhere as 'do not stake', but `_updateConvexPool()` always reads `poolInfo(currentPid)`, withdraws only the old reward-contract balance, and then blindly deposits `stakedBalance` into `_pid`, including when `_pid == 0`. It also ignores any collateral already sitting locally when migrating from `0` to a live pool. Since `totalCollateral()` switches between local-balance and reward-contract accounting based only on `convexPid`, changing pools across the sentinel can make the contract look in the wrong place for essentially all collateral.","impact":"An owner pool update can make the pair believe collateral vanished, causing withdrawals and liquidations to revert or positions to appear insolvent even though the tokens still exist somewhere else. This is a protocol-level lockup/orphaning risk for all live collateral in the pair.","paths":["If the owner calls `setConvexPool(0)` to disable staking, `_updateConvexPool()` withdraws from the old rewards contract and then deposits the same amount into Convex pool `0`, but sets `convexPid = 0`; afterwards `totalCollateral()` reads only the pair's local collateral balance and ignores the still-staked funds.","If the pair currently has `convexPid == 0` and already holds local collateral, calling `setConvexPool(nonZeroPid)` migrates only `stakedBalance` read from `poolInfo(0)` and never stakes the pair's local holdings; afterwards `totalCollateral()` reads only the Convex reward balance and ignores the locally held collateral.","Any subsequent withdrawal, liquidation, or solvency path that relies on `totalCollateral()` / `_unstakeUnderlying()` can then fail against the mismatched accounting location."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Unconditional reward claiming can globally freeze borrowing, repayments, withdrawals, and liquidations","locations":["src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:224","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:226","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:321","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:599","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:833"],"claim":"Every borrower checkpoint unconditionally calls `IResupplyRegistry(registry).claimRewards(address(this))`. Checkpoints sit inside `_syncUserRedemptions()` and `_repay()`, which are reached by `isSolvent`-gated borrow/collateral flows, normal repayments, and liquidations. As a result, any revert in the registry reward-claim path bricks core pair operations even though reward collection is ancillary bookkeeping.","impact":"If the reward claimer, registry hook, or downstream reward source starts reverting, active borrowers can be unable to borrow, remove collateral, repay, repay with collateral, or be liquidated. That can trap user positions and let insolvencies persist because liquidation is blocked by an unrelated reward failure.","paths":["`borrow`, `removeCollateral*`, `leveragedPosition`, and `repayWithCollateral` all execute the `isSolvent` modifier, which calls `_syncUserRedemptions()` -> `_checkpoint()` -> `_fetchIncentives()` -> external `claimRewards` before the main action completes.","`repay` and the liquidation path both call `_repay()`, which also checkpoints the borrower before updating debt and therefore hits the same external reward-claim dependency.","If `claimRewards(address(this))` reverts for any reason, those state-changing entrypoints revert as well, causing a pair-wide DoS for debt management and liquidations."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Zero oracle prices cause division-by-zero reverts across critical pair flows","locations":["src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:573","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:688","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:955","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:1001"],"claim":"`_updateExchangeRate()` computes `1e36 / IOracle(...).getPrices(...)` without checking that the oracle returned a non-zero price. If the configured oracle ever returns `0` instead of reverting, the division hard-reverts every caller that refreshes the exchange rate.","impact":"A zero oracle answer can halt borrowing, leveraged positions, redemptions, liquidations, and collateral withdrawals for borrowers that still have debt. This can trap positions and block liquidations during exactly the period when the price feed is unhealthy.","paths":["The configured oracle or one of its downstream feeds returns `0` for `getPrices(address(collateral))`.","Any call path that executes `_updateExchangeRate()`—including `borrow`, `leveragedPosition`, `repayWithCollateral`, `redeemCollateral`, `liquidate`, and collateral removal for users with outstanding debt—reverts on division by zero.","Because solvency updates and liquidation both depend on a fresh exchange rate, active positions can become unmanageable until the oracle stops returning zero."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-009","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Share-refactor floor rounding can leak small amounts of debt and leave unowned borrow shares","locations":["src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:336","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:944","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:946"],"claim":"When a redemption triggers share refactoring, the pair divides `totalBorrow.shares` by `SHARE_REFACTOR_PRECISION` once, but each borrower's `_userBorrowShares` is only divided later during `_increaseUserRewardEpoch()` using floor rounding. There is no remainder accounting, so the sum of lazily-updated user shares can fall below the already-refactored global share total, and borrowers with fewer than `SHARE_REFACTOR_PRECISION` pre-refactor shares round all the way to zero.","impact":"The loss per account is bounded and typically small, but it can permanently leak some debt out of user ownership. In edge cases, a dust borrower can become debt-free after a refactor while the corresponding amount remains embedded in global debt accounting, creating small accounting drift and redistributing residual debt away from rounded-down users.","paths":["Repeated redemptions reduce `totalBorrow.amount` until `totalBorrow.amount * SHARE_REFACTOR_PRECISION < totalBorrow.shares`, triggering `_increaseRewardEpoch()` and a one-time division of global borrow shares.","Borrowers are migrated to the new epoch lazily, and each `_userBorrowShares` value is independently divided by `SHARE_REFACTOR_PRECISION` with floor rounding.","After enough borrowers sync, the sum of user-owned shares can be smaller than `totalBorrow.shares`; very small positions can round to zero shares entirely and stop owing their residual debt."],"round":3,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-010","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Excess redemption write-offs are silently discarded, leaving phantom collateral in borrower accounting","locations":["src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:279","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:604","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:610","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:965"],"claim":"Redemptions socialize collateral losses by minting `redemptionWriteOff` rewards pro rata to borrow shares, but `_syncUserRedemptions()` caps each borrower's loss at zero collateral and then erases the full claimable write-off balance. If an account's assigned write-off exceeds its current `_userCollateralBalance`, the excess loss is dropped instead of being redistributed or booked as bad debt. `_isSolvent()` later trusts the raw `_userCollateralBalance` value, so the remaining borrowers can still appear better collateralized than the pair's actual post-redemption collateral supports.","impact":"After a large redemption, the system can become materially undercollateralized while some borrowers still look solvent on paper. Those borrowers can then withdraw real collateral or take on more debt against collateral that has already been redeemed away, draining the remaining pool and worsening insolvency for everyone left.","paths":["A redemption removes collateral from the pair and mints `redemptionWriteOff` in proportion to current borrow shares.","A highly leveraged borrower's pending write-off exceeds its `_userCollateralBalance`, so `_syncUserRedemptions()` floors that account to zero at `currentUserBalance >= rTokens ? currentUserBalance - rTokens : 0` and discards the excess by zeroing `claimable_reward[address(redemptionWriteOff)][account]`.","The pair's actual collateral fell by the full redeemed amount, but aggregate borrower collateral is reduced by less than that full amount.","Later solvency checks and collateral actions use the overstated `_userCollateralBalance`, allowing other borrowers to borrow more or withdraw against phantom backing until real collateral runs out."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-012","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Allowing `minimumLeftoverDebt = 0` can preserve stale global borrow shares after full redemption","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:289","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:936","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:944","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:946","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:649","src/libraries/VaultAccount.sol:16"],"claim":"The owner can set `minimumLeftoverDebt` to zero, which allows `redeemCollateral()` to drive `totalBorrow.amount` fully to zero. The subsequent share refactor only divides `totalBorrow.shares` by `SHARE_REFACTOR_PRECISION` once, so nonzero global borrow shares can remain even though total debt is zero. Later borrows call `toShares()` with `total.amount == 0`, which mints new shares without clearing those leftovers, carrying stale share supply into the next debt cycle.","impact":"Post-redemption debt accounting can start from a corrupted share base instead of a clean reset. Newly opened borrows can be diluted by unowned stale shares, leaving part of the new global debt effectively unattached to any borrower and causing misallocation in later repayment and solvency math.","paths":["Governance sets `minimumLeftoverDebt` to `0` through `setMinimumLeftoverDebt()`.","A redemption reduces `totalBorrow.amount` to zero, but the one-shot refactor in `redeemCollateral()` leaves `totalBorrow.shares > 0`.","A later borrower opens a new position; `_totalBorrow.toShares(debtForMint, true)` follows the `total.amount == 0` branch and mints fresh shares on top of the stale share supply instead of resetting it.","The resulting `totalBorrow.amount` / `totalBorrow.shares` state includes leftover unowned shares, skewing future debt ownership and accounting."],"round":4,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-013","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Reward-manager invalidation can disable the internal write-off token and break redemption accounting","locations":["src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:125","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:129","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:150","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:177","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:604","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:965"],"claim":"`invalidateReward()` can be called on any tracked reward token, including the internally-created `redemptionWriteOff` token registered in the pair constructor. Once that slot is invalidated, `_calcRewardIntegral()` returns early for it, so new write-off supply minted by `redeemCollateral()` never reaches `claimable_reward[address(redemptionWriteOff)]` and `_syncUserRedemptions()` stops reducing borrower collateral for subsequent redemptions. If the token is revived later, the skipped backlog is then distributed using the borrow-share distribution at revival time rather than the historical distribution when the redemptions occurred.","impact":"A mistaken or unsafe reward-manager action can temporarily disable the pair's redemption-loss accounting, leaving borrower collateral overstated after redemptions. During that window borrowers can avoid liquidations, borrow against collateral that has already been redeemed away, or withdraw more collateral than the pair still owns; reviving the token later can then socialize the missed losses onto the wrong borrowers.","paths":["The reward manager calls `invalidateReward(address(redemptionWriteOff))`.","One or more redemptions occur, and `redeemCollateral()` keeps minting additional write-off supply.","Borrowers are checkpointed through normal actions, but `_syncUserRedemptions()` sees no new `claimable_reward[address(redemptionWriteOff)]`, so their collateral balances are not reduced for those redemptions.","If the reward token is later revived, the entire skipped write-off backlog is assigned across the then-current borrow-share distribution instead of the historical one."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-016","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Constructor bypasses the max-LTV safety cap enforced by the runtime setter","locations":["src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:141","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:173","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:193"],"claim":"The constructor decodes `_maxLTV` from deployment config and writes it directly into storage without checking that it is at most `LTV_PRECISION`, while `setMaxLTV()` later rejects values above that cap. A pair can therefore be deployed with a max LTV above 100% even though the live setter forbids that state.","impact":"A misconfigured deployment can launch an already unsafe market where users permissionlessly open undercollateralized positions and extract bad debt up to the configured borrow limit. Because the protocol explicitly enforces the bound in the runtime setter, the missing constructor check is a real initialization gap rather than an intended operating mode.","paths":["A pair is deployed with constructor config `_maxLTV > 1e5`.","Users add a small amount of collateral and borrow more value than the collateral can support while still passing `_isSolvent()` against the inflated limit.","The pair accumulates immediate bad debt even though the same max-LTV value could never be set after deployment via `setMaxLTV()`."],"round":5,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-019","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Any registered reward token that misbehaves can freeze borrower-facing pair operations","locations":["src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:147","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:158","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:224","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:599","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:840"],"claim":"Every `_checkpoint()` iterates the full registered reward list and blindly calls each reward token's `balanceOf(address(this))`; claim paths also attempt `safeTransfer()` for claimable rewards. Because checkpoints are embedded in `_syncUserRedemptions()` and `_repay()`, a single registered reward token that reverts or becomes non-standard can revert the entire action path until the reward manager manually invalidates it.","impact":"Borrowing, repaying, removing collateral, `repayWithCollateral`, liquidating, and reward claiming can all become unavailable because checkpointing is a prerequisite for those flows. A bad reward asset therefore creates a protocol-level liveness failure even though rewards are ancillary bookkeeping.","paths":["A reward token is registered via `addExtraReward()` (or already exists) and later starts reverting on `balanceOf()` or reward transfer behavior.","A user calls any path that checkpoints rewards, such as `borrow()`, `removeCollateral()`, `repay()`, `repayWithCollateral()`, or `liquidate()`.","`_calcRewardIntegral()` reverts while processing the bad reward token, so the enclosing checkpoint and the entire operation revert until the token is invalidated."],"round":6,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-021","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Interest overflow silently forgives accrued debt and permanently skips the elapsed interval","locations":["src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:481","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:484","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:492","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:533","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:537"],"claim":"If accrued interest would push `totalBorrow.amount` above `uint128.max`, `_calculateInterest()` zeroes `interestEarned` instead of saturating or reverting, but `_addInterest()` still advances `lastTimestamp`, updates the rate state, and writes the unchanged borrow total back to storage. The elapsed interval's interest is therefore discarded forever.","impact":"Once debt approaches the `uint128` ceiling, borrowers can stop paying meaningful interest for any interval whose accrual exceeds the remaining headroom. The pair undercharges debt, loses protocol fees, and can accumulate insolvency because near-cap borrows effectively stop accruing for skipped intervals.","paths":["Borrowers drive `totalBorrow.amount` near `type(uint128).max` within the configured borrow limit.","They wait until `_deltaTime * totalBorrow.amount * newRate / RATE_PRECISION` exceeds the remaining `uint128` headroom.","Any action that calls `_addInterest()` hits the overflow branch, resets `interestEarned` to zero, but still sets `currentRateInfo.lastTimestamp = block.timestamp` and persists the new rate state.","The skipped interval cannot be recovered later, and the same pattern can repeat whenever debt remains near the cap."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-022","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Invalidating a reward token strands already accrued user rewards and pair-held balances","locations":["src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:129","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:136","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:152","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:281","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:302"],"claim":"`invalidateReward()` zeroes the tracked reward slot's token address. After that, `_calcRewardIntegral()` returns early for the slot and both `earned()` and `getReward()` skip it entirely. Any `claimable_reward[token][user]` already accrued, plus any balance of that token already sitting in the pair, becomes inaccessible unless that exact token is later revived into the same slot.","impact":"Emergency reward invalidation can confiscate already-earned CRV/CVX/governance rewards from borrowers and strand reward tokens inside the pair. If the token is invalidated because claims are unsafe or permanently broken, users may never recover those rewards.","paths":["Users accrue claimable amounts for a reward token, or the pair already holds a balance of that token.","The reward manager calls `invalidateReward(token)`.","Future checkpoints skip the slot because `reward.reward_token == address(0)`.","`earned()` and `getReward()` no longer surface or transfer the previously accrued rewards unless governance later revives the exact same token entry."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-023","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Constructor bypasses the liquidation-fee and protocol-redemption-fee caps enforced by runtime setters","locations":["src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:168","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:170","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:230","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:233","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:306","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:307"],"claim":"The constructor writes `_liquidationFee` and `_protocolRedemptionFee` from deployment config straight into storage, but the runtime setters later reject liquidation fees above `LIQ_PRECISION` and protocol redemption fees above `EXCHANGE_PRECISION`. A pair can therefore be deployed with fee values that the live admin interface explicitly considers invalid.","impact":"A misconfigured deployment can launch a market with pathological fees: oversized liquidation fees let liquidations seize far more collateral than intended, potentially all of a borrower's collateral, while oversized protocol redemption fees can overcharge or even make redemptions revert via `debtReduction = _amount - protocolFee`. This can create immediate user loss, bad debt, or broken redemptions from day one.","paths":["A pair is deployed with `_liquidationFee > LIQ_PRECISION` and/or `_protocolRedemptionFee > EXCHANGE_PRECISION`.","The constructor stores those values without validation even though the corresponding runtime setters would revert.","Liquidations then compute `collateralForLiquidator` using the invalid liquidation premium, or redemptions compute `protocolFee` using an invalid protocol fee share.","Users interact with a market whose fee behavior could never be configured post-deployment, leading to excessive collateral seizure, skewed redemption accounting, or redemption reverts."],"round":7,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-025","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Mint fee is uncapped, so governance can make new borrows immediately confiscatory","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:251","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:169","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:640","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:662"],"claim":"Neither the constructor nor `setMintFees()` enforce an upper bound on `mintFee`, even though analogous risk parameters like `liquidationFee` and `protocolRedemptionFee` are capped. `_borrow()` books debt as `borrowAmount * (LIQ_PRECISION + mintFee) / LIQ_PRECISION` while minting only `_borrowAmount` debt tokens to the receiver, so a large mint fee can charge borrowers far more debt than the value they receive.","impact":"A bad governance action or misconfiguration can turn `borrow()` and `leveragedPosition()` into direct value extraction: users receive a small amount of debt token but are saddled with a much larger liability, protocol-claimable `claimableOtherFees` can balloon, and new positions can become immediately distressed or insolvent.","paths":["The pair is deployed with, or the owner later sets, an extreme `mintFee`.","A user opens or increases a position through `borrow()` or `leveragedPosition()`.","`_borrow()` records the inflated `debtForMint`, credits the excess to `claimableOtherFees`, and mints only `_borrowAmount` to the receiver, leaving the borrower overcharged for the transaction."],"round":8,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-026","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Oracle and rate-calculator setters accept invalid addresses and can globally brick the pair","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:176","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:208","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:474","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:573"],"claim":"`setOracle()` and `setRateCalculator()` perform no zero-address or contract-code validation. If either pointer is updated to `address(0)` or an EOA, the next `_updateExchangeRate()` or `_addInterest()` call reverts when the pair tries to call `getPrices()` or `getNewRate()` on a non-contract.","impact":"A single bad configuration can freeze core pair behavior. Because interest accrual and exchange-rate refresh are prerequisites for borrow, collateral removal, repay paths that accrue interest, redemptions, and liquidations, the market can become unusable until governance repairs the address; if governance access is simultaneously impaired, the freeze can persist indefinitely.","paths":["The owner calls `setOracle(address(0))` or points it at an EOA; the next path that reaches `_updateExchangeRate()` reverts.","The owner calls `setRateCalculator(address(0))` or points it at an EOA; the next path that reaches `_addInterest()` reverts.","Core user flows depend on those helpers, so the bad pointer bricks borrowing, debt management, redemptions, and liquidation until a valid contract is restored."],"round":8,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-029","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Convex pool configuration never validates that a `pid` matches the pair collateral","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:51","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:57","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:377","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:382","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:399","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:406","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:413","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:421"],"claim":"Both the constructor and `setConvexPool()` accept any nonzero Convex `pid` without checking that the booster pool's LP token and reward wrapper correspond to this pair's `collateral`. Once such a pid is stored, `_stakeUnderlying()`, `_unstakeUnderlying()`, and `totalCollateral()` all start interacting with whatever pool and reward contract `poolInfo(pid)` returns.","impact":"A bad pool id can make collateral staking and unstaking revert, or make the pair read collateral balances from the wrong reward wrapper. That can leave the market unusable or make live collateral effectively invisible to solvency, withdrawal, redemption, and liquidation paths until governance repairs the configuration.","paths":["The pair is deployed with, or the owner later sets, a nonzero `convexPid` whose `poolInfo(pid).lptoken` / rewards contract do not match this pair's collateral.","After the update, `_stakeUnderlying()` deposits into the wrong Convex pool and `_unstakeUnderlying()` / `totalCollateral()` query the wrong reward contract.","Collateral additions, withdrawals, redemptions, or liquidations then revert or operate against incorrect staking balances, causing protocol-level lockup or broken accounting."],"round":9,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-030","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Uncapped `minimumBorrowAmount` can make partial repayments and deleveraging impossible for existing borrowers","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:296","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:635","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:852","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:1241"],"claim":"`setMinimumBorrowAmount()` imposes no upper bound, while `_repay()` reverts whenever a borrower would be left with a nonzero debt position below `minimumBorrowAmount`. Raising the threshold above existing positions therefore converts repayment from a flexible paydown flow into an all-or-nothing requirement.","impact":"A bad governance action or misconfiguration can trap users in risky positions by blocking partial `repay()` and `repayWithCollateral()` transactions that would otherwise reduce leverage. Borrowers who cannot source a full repayment in one transaction may be forced to remain exposed until liquidation.","paths":["The owner raises `minimumBorrowAmount` above an existing borrower's remaining debt, or above the residual debt that would remain after a planned paydown.","The borrower attempts a partial `repay()` or `repayWithCollateral()` deleveraging transaction.","`_repay()` reverts because `usershares > 0` and the recomputed remaining debt is below `minimumBorrowAmount`, leaving only full repayment as an allowed exit."],"round":9,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-031","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Zero `epochLength` in the core contract permanently bricks pair fee withdrawals","locations":["src/interfaces/ICore.sol:17","src/dependencies/EpochTracker.sol:16","src/dependencies/EpochTracker.sol:21","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:322","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:330"],"claim":"`EpochTracker` copies `ICore(_core).epochLength()` into an immutable without validating it is nonzero, and `getEpoch()` later divides by that value. `withdrawFees()` unconditionally calls `getEpoch()`, so a pair deployed against a core reporting `epochLength == 0` can never withdraw accrued fees.","impact":"Interest fees and other protocol fees can become permanently stranded in the pair. This does not directly steal user funds, but it can lock protocol revenue and break the intended fee-distribution flow for the life of the deployment.","paths":["A pair is deployed against a core contract whose `epochLength()` returns `0`.","Fees accrue normally in `claimableFees` / `claimableOtherFees`.","Any call to `withdrawFees()` reaches `getEpoch()`, which divides by zero and reverts, leaving fee withdrawal permanently unavailable."],"round":9,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Redemption path releases collateral without any pair-side proof that debt tokens were paid or burned","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`redeemCollateral()` is intentionally restricted to the registry-configured `redemptionHandler`; whether and how debt is burned is delegated to that trusted system component, so this depends on privileged-handler compromise or out-of-scope handler bugs rather than a pair-side invariant violation."},{"title":"Liquidation clears borrower debt before verifying the insurance-side burn actually happened","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"`liquidate()` is intentionally callable only by the registry-configured `liquidationHandler`, and the comment/documented flow explicitly delegates the burn to `processLiquidationDebt`; absent a bug in that trusted handler, this is an architectural trust assumption rather than a standalone pair vulnerability."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/audithoundv2/output/resupply_fi_1777184922/rounds/round_2/merge_stdout.log:1:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Oracle decimal scaling is ignored, so non-18-decimal feeds misprice collateral by orders of magnitude","locations":["src/interfaces/IOracle.sol:5","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:573","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:176"],"claim":"The pair hardcodes exchange-rate inversion as `1e36 / oraclePrice` and never normalizes by `IOracle.decimals()`, even though the oracle interface exposes a decimals field and `setOracle()` accepts arbitrary replacement feeds. Any oracle returning prices in a scale other than 18 decimals will distort the collateral/debt conversion by a power-of-ten factor.","impact":"Borrow, solvency, redemption, and liquidation math can all be wrong by orders of magnitude. Depending on the oracle scale, healthy positions can be liquidated or blocked from withdrawing, or collateral can be overvalued enough for borrowers to mint far more debt than intended, leaving the pair insolvent.","paths":["A pair is deployed with, or later updated to, an oracle whose `getPrices()` output is not 18-decimal scaled.","`_updateExchangeRate()` computes `exchangeRate = 1e36 / price` without using `IOracle.decimals()`.","The distorted exchange rate propagates into `_isSolvent()`, borrow limits, redemptions, and liquidations."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Rewards claimed while no borrow shares exist become permanently stranded in the pair","locations":["src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:162","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:200","src/protocol/RewardDistributorMultiEpoch.sol:302","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:321","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:325"],"claim":"Reward accrual is only added to `global_reward_integral` when `_totalRewardShares() > 0`, but `_checkpoint()` still calls `_fetchIncentives()` and `_calcRewardIntegral()` still updates `reward_remaining = bal` even when reward shares are zero. Because `getReward` is publicly callable and `totalRewardShares` is just `totalBorrow.shares`, any rewards fetched during a zero-debt period are marked as already-accounted without increasing any user/global integral, so the backlog can never be distributed later.","impact":"CRV/CVX/governance rewards accrued while collateral remains staked but no borrows exist can be permanently trapped in the pair. This causes real value loss to the reward program/borrower set, and it is permissionless because any caller can trigger a checkpoint or `getReward` during the zero-share window.","paths":["Collateral remains staked in Convex while `totalBorrow.shares == 0`.","External rewards accrue and any caller triggers `getReward`, `earned`, or another checkpoint path, which calls `claimRewards(address(this))`.","`_calcRewardIntegral` skips integral growth because `_totalRewardShares() == 0` but still stores the fetched balance in `reward_remaining`.","When borrowing later resumes, only rewards above that stored balance are distributable; the earlier fetched balance remains stuck in the pair with no recovery path."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Unchecked Convex staking results can leave credited collateral unstaked and later lock withdrawals/liquidations","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:399","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:409","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:421","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:713","src/protocol/pair/ResupplyPairCore.sol:769"],"claim":"When Convex mode is enabled, the pair credits user collateral first and then calls `IConvexStaking.deposit(...)` without checking its boolean return value. `totalCollateral()` only counts the reward-contract stake balance, so if a Convex deposit returns `false` or stakes less than expected, the pair's accounting assumes collateral was staked while later exits try to withdraw shares that never reached Convex.","impact":"User collateral can become effectively stuck: withdrawals, liquidations, or pool migrations can revert because `_unstakeUnderlying()` pulls from the reward contract while the missing collateral remains idle in the pair. This creates accounting divergence and can permissionlessly DoS collateral exits for affected positions.","paths":["A borrower adds collateral while `convexPid != 0`, or the owner migrates pools with `_updateConvexPool()`.","The Convex `deposit(..., true)` call returns `false` or under-stakes, but the pair ignores the result and still keeps the higher `_userCollateralBalance`.","Later `_removeCollateral()` or pool migration calls `_unstakeUnderlying()` for the credited amount, but the reward contract balance is lower than expected, causing the operation to fail."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Convex pool migration mishandles the sentinel `pid == 0` and can orphan all collateral","locations":["src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:382","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:386","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:399","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:402","src/protocol/ResupplyPair.sol:421"],"claim":"`convexPid == 0` is treated elsewhere as 'do not stake', but `_updateConvexPool()` always reads `poolInfo(currentPid)`, withdraws only the old reward-contract balance, and then blindly deposits `stakedBalance` into `_pid`, including when `_pid == 0`. It also ignores any collateral already sitting locally when migrating from `0` to a live pool. Since `totalCollateral()` switches between local-balance and reward-contract accounting based only on `convexPid`, changing pools across the sentinel can make the contract look in the wrong place for essentially all collateral.","impact":"An owner pool update can make the pair believe collateral vanished, causing withdrawals and liquidations to revert or positions to appear insolvent even though the tokens still exist somewhere else. This is a protocol-level lockup/orphaning risk for all live collateral in the pair.","paths":["If the owner calls `setConvexPool(0)` to disable staking, `_updateConvexPool()` withdraws from the old rewards contract and then deposits the same amount into Convex pool `0`, but sets `convexPid = 0`; afterwards `totalCollateral()` reads only the pair's local collateral balance and ignores the still-staked funds.","If the pair currently has `convexPid == 0` and already holds local collateral, calling `setConvexPool(nonZeroPid)` migrates only `stakedBalance` read from `poolInfo(0)` and never stakes the pair's local holdings; afterwards `totalCollateral()` reads only the Convex reward balance and ignores the locally held collateral.","Any subsequent withdrawal, liquidation, or solvency path that relies on `totalCollateral()` / `_unstakeUnderlying()` can then fail against the mismatched accounting location."],"round":2,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Redemption protocol fees are double-counted unless the external handler burns the full input amount","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"The mismatch hinges on how the out-of-scope redemption handler burns debt. The pair comments are inconsistent, but the code in this repo alone does not show an actual double-mint; this is an external integration assumption rather than a concrete protocol bug here."}]}
